{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566836"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:49:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:49:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18885"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18885"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.25,0.51,0.01,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11618"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86278"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11618"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18885"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70556"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1594"},{"type":"tags","id":"2793"},{"type":"tags","id":"3736"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27345"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86278"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for routine follow-up of polycythaemia vera. She was diagnosed two years ago following investigation of pruritus and elevated haemoglobin. She has no significant medical history apart from hypertension, for which she takes amlodipine. She undergoes regular therapeutic venesection every eight weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Recent blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 135 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaematocrit 0.42 (0.33-0.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean cell volume 75 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFerritin 12 \u00b5g/L (20-200)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVitamin B12 350 pmol/L (200-680)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFolate 25 nmol/L (7-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cease venesection","Continue current venesection schedule","Oral iron supplementation","Vitamin B12 replacement","Intravenous iron infusion"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has polycythaemia vera with evidence of iron deficiency (low ferritin and microcytosis) but normal haemoglobin and haematocrit levels. This represents good disease control with therapeutic venesection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue current venesection schedule\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Iron deficiency in patients with polycythaemia vera who are undergoing therapeutic venesection is expected and actually indicates good disease control. The iron deficiency helps limit erythropoiesis and maintain target haematocrit levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous iron infusion\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it would stimulate increased red cell production, potentially leading to loss of disease control and increased thrombotic risk. Iron replacement in polycythaemia vera should generally be avoided unless there are compelling reasons such as severe symptomatic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral iron supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E, like intravenous iron, would be contraindicated for the same reasons. Even oral iron supplementation could lead to increased red cell production and loss of disease control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin B12 replacement\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the vitamin B12 level is normal. Furthermore, vitamin B12 supplementation in the absence of deficiency would not affect the course of polycythaemia vera.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease venesection\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as the patient\u0027s disease is well-controlled on the current regimen. Stopping venesection would likely lead to a rise in haematocrit and increased thrombotic risk. The target haematocrit in polycythaemia vera is \u0026lt;0.45 to reduce complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Iron deficiency in polycythaemia vera patients on therapeutic venesection indicates good disease control and should not be corrected.","Therapeutic venesection in polycythaemia vera aims to maintain haematocrit \u003C0.45 to reduce thrombotic risk.","Iron replacement in polycythaemia vera can lead to increased red cell production and loss of disease control."],"references":["Tefferi A, Barbui T. Polycythemia vera: 2024 update on diagnosis, risk-stratification, and management. American Journal of Hematology. 2023;98(9):1465\u201387. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37357958/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70556"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18885"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70556"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-20T13:01:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-20T13:01:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11618"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86278"}